# Database Layer — Trellis PostgreSQL + Drizzle

## Schema Conventions
- UUID primary keys via gen_random_uuid() (switch to uuidv7() when RDS supports PG 18)
- `tenant_id BIGINT NOT NULL` denormalized on EVERY tenant-scoped table (first column after PK)
- `created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()` and `updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()` on all tables
- RLS policy on all tenant-scoped tables: `USING (tenant_id = (SELECT current_tenant_id()) AND (SELECT current_tenant_id()) IS NOT NULL)`
- `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` on table owners to prevent bypassing
- `btree_gist` extension enabled for temporal EXCLUDE constraints

## Multi-Tenancy (37 tables, 7 domains)
- Platform tables (NO RLS): tenants, users
- Shared reference tables (special RLS): compliance_profiles — platform/state scope rows readable by all via app_admin; community-scoped rows use tenant_id RLS
- All other tables: RLS-enforced tenant isolation
- Platform-level access: separate connection pool with BYPASSRLS role (super_admin only)

## Drizzle ORM
- Schema files organized by domain: `schema/platform.ts`, `schema/community.ts`, `schema/financial.ts`, `schema/governance.ts`, `schema/operations.ts`, `schema/communications.ts`
- Use Drizzle's pgTable, pgEnum, and relation definitions
- Map snake_case SQL columns to camelCase TypeScript via column naming
- Generate migrations with `drizzle-kit generate` — never write migration SQL by hand
- Review generated SQL before applying with `drizzle-kit migrate`

## Column Patterns
- Status columns: use CHECK constraints with string unions, NOT enums (easier to evolve)
- Monetary amounts: `NUMERIC(12,2)` — NEVER use float/double for money
- Temporal ownership: `daterange` columns with GiST-backed EXCLUDE constraints
- JSONB: for configuration bundles, sparse data, tenant-extensible fields — NEVER for data you query/filter/sort
- Text arrays: `TEXT[]` with GIN indexes for tag-based search (violation categories, precedent tags)

## Indexing Strategy
- Composite index leading on `tenant_id` for all tenant-scoped queries
- Partial indexes for common filters: `WHERE status != 'active'`, `WHERE upper(valid_during) IS NULL`
- GIN indexes on JSONB columns that need key-based queries
- GiST indexes on daterange columns for temporal queries
- Full-text search: tsvector columns with GIN indexes (documents, violation descriptions)

## State Machines in SQL
- Append-only transition tables (violation_transitions, arc_transitions)
- Current state stored on parent table for query performance
- Transition table records: from_state, to_state, triggered_by, timestamp, metadata (JSONB)
- Transition rules table defines valid state transitions per state jurisdiction
- Application code validates transitions against rules before INSERT

## Financial Data
- Fund-tagged double-entry ledger pattern
- Payment-to-charge application via junction table (supports partial payments, overpayments)
- Assessment rate history table tracks all changes with effective dates
- Immutable audit log for all financial operations

## Migrations
- Always test migrations against a copy of production data
- Wrap DDL in transactions where possible
- Add NOT NULL columns with DEFAULT first, backfill, then optionally drop default
- Never rename columns — add new, migrate data, drop old
- Index creation: use CONCURRENTLY for large tables to avoid locks
